Dr '''Christopher Ian "Chris" Higgins''' (3 April 1943{{spaced endash}}6 December 1990) was a senior Australian public servant and economist. He was [[Departmental secretary|Secretary]] of the [[Department of the Treasury (Australia)|Department of the Treasury]] from September 1989 until his death.

==Life and career==
Chris Higgins was born in [[Murwillumbah, New South Wales]] on 3 April 1943.<ref name=Keating>{{citation|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/higgins-christopher-ian-chris-12633|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423231157/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/higgins-christopher-ian-chris-12633|archivedate=23 April 2014|title=Higgins, Christopher Ian (Chris) (1943–1990)|first=Michael|last=Keating|author-link=Michael Keating (public servant)|publisher=Australian National University|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography}}</ref> He attended [[Ballina High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.acu.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/341949/CTimes.pdf|title=The top of Treasury's talented table|page=14|newspaper=The Canberra Times|first=J.R.|last=Nethercote|date=7 June 2011|archivedate=23 April 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423232319/http://www.acu.edu.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0003/341949/CTimes.pdf}}</ref>

In 1960, Higgins came to [[Canberra]] as a Commonwealth Bureau of Statistics Cadet.<ref name=Stone>{{citation|url=http://www.assa.edu.au/fellowship/fellow/deceased/100143|title=Dr Christopher Higgins|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140302080125/http://www.assa.edu.au/fellowship/fellow/deceased/100143|archivedate=2 March 2014|publisher=Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia|first=John|last=Stone|author-link=John Stone (Australian politician)}}</ref> He graduated in 1964 from the Canberra University College (now known as the [[Australian National University]]) with a Bachelor of Economics with first class honours in economics and statistics.<ref name=Stone/> He then won a postgraduate scholarship to study for his doctorate at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] under supervisor [[Lawrence Klein]].<ref name=Stone/>

Between 1975 and 1989, Higgins was a Senior Executive Officer in the Department of the Treasury, including as a Deputy Secretary from 1984.<ref name=Hawke>{{cite press release|url=http://pmtranscripts.dpmc.gov.au/browse.php?did=7671|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423232648/http://pmtranscripts.dpmc.gov.au/browse.php?did=7671|archivedate=23 April 2014|title=Unknown|first=Robert|last=Hawke|author-link=Bob Hawke|date=5 July 1989}}</ref> He was appointed Secretary of the department in September 1989.<ref name=Hawke/>

Higgins died in [[Bruce, Australian Capital Territory]] from heart failure on 6 December 1990, aged 47, having just won a {{convert|3|km}} footrace.<ref name=Stone/>

The {{citation|url=https://www.anu.edu.au/students/program-administration/prizes/chris-higgins-prize|title=Chris Higgins Prize}} given for outstanding graduate study in Economics at the [[Australian National University]] is named for him.

